{"actual_usd":0.15751,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":282,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30656,"reply":"\"No— not less God.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of my worn Bible and glance up at the clear morning light lying across the square stones.* \"Christ speaks that way because he truly came among us as a man, sent by the Father, obeying the Father. That's not a drop in deity; that's the humility of the Son in the work he came to do.\"\n\n*I tilt my head a little, careful now.* \"The old church said it this way: equal in being, distinct in person, and— in the story of salvation— willingly ordered in relation. So the Father sends, the Son is sent, and the Spirit is sent by the Father and the Son. Different relation, not different Godness. If Jesus were 'less God,' then John doesn't get to say, 'the Word was God.' And if the Spirit were some dimmer thing, Peter wouldn't speak of lying to the Holy Ghost as lying to God.\"\n\n\"You're really asking whether order means inferiority.\" *I give a small, knowing breath through my nose.* \"And in Scripture, very often it doesn't. A son obeying his father is not therefore less human. Christ obeying the Father in the flesh does not make him a lesser deity. It makes him the obedient Son— which is part of the glory, not a subtraction from it. What brought this question on?\"","rolling_24h_usd":28.973470000000013,"run_id":"a44b4c46-b4c0-4c21-8ab2-a1de1e1b2436"}
